content:
You can test out Service Cloud Voice with your telephony provider in your sandbox. Before you set up Voice in a sandbox, follow these best practices to prepare the environment and to migrate data.

This feature is available with Amazon Connect telephony models.

To learn how to refresh your Service Cloud Voice with Amazon Connect sandbox, go to the Service Cloud Voice Implementation Guide.

When you set up Voice in a sandbox, Salesforce creates an Amazon Web Services (AWS) subaccount and an Amazon Connect instance for you. Charges for your Amazon usage in the sandbox are charged to the production org.

To access Amazon Web Services documentation, go to https://docs.aws.amazon.com.

If Voice is set up in a sandbox, only do a Partial Copy sandbox refresh. If you do a full refresh, you have to set up Voice again.

When you're finished using Voice in your sandbox, delete your Amazon Connect instance, so your org doesn't incur more charges for Amazon Connect usage.

Delete Existing Contact Centers

Copy the data from your production org to the sandbox.
Delete the call center information from the sandbox.
Disable the identity provider.
Delete the contact center. When you delete the contact center, the connected app and connected app data are also deleted.

Migrate Data from AWS and Salesforce

Import Voice sample contact flows into Amazon Connect.
Salesforce creates an Amazon Connect instance when you create a contact center in Voice. If you have other Connect instance configurations, you must manually reconfigure them.
Migrate the contact center information.
Migrate users associated with the contact center. Use the Data Loader to migrate users.
Export and deploy the configuration files from the connected app.

Delete Instance and Close AWS Account

Refer to Amazon documentation to delete your Amazon Connect instance and close your AWS account.
